title: QLinearAdd support
Support to allow user to specify compute stream per session
body:
Create computation cuda stream explicitly rather than use default legacy stream or per-thread default stream.

CUDA has two kinds of default stream. One is called legacy default stream. The other is called per-thread default stream which was introduced since CUDA 7. Here are details: https://devblogs.nvidia.com/gpu-pro-tip-cuda-7-streams-simplify-concurrency/

At beginning, CUDA EP was implemented with per-thread default stream. But, cudnn, cublas were still execute on legacy stream. That is to say, handcrafted CUDA kernels in ORT are running on per-thread stream, but cudnn/cublas kernels are running on legacy stream. And implicitly, these two streams are synchronized. During training development, we found that this synchronization caused overhead. For example, for BERT-L training, forcing all kernels to one stream will increase training throughput about 8%. For inference, we saw latency decrease too. 

Due to time constraint, per-thread default stream was disabled and instead legacy default stream was enabled in current CUDA EP.

The below are what this PR addresses.
1. Allow users to specify the stream they want to use through OrtCUDAProviderOptions. That is to say, with the current implementation, the users can specify the stream per ORT session. Later, we may improve it to allow user to specify stream per ORT run call.
2. If users don't specify the stream, then ORT will create a compute stream explicitly by calling cudaStreamCreateWithFlags with cudaStreamNonBlocking, which means compute stream in ORT won't synchronize with legacy default stream. The plan is that after this PR, we should not use legacy default stream or per-thread default stream anymore. Instead, all of GPU kernels should be launched in this compute stream. That is to say, for every handcrafted CUDA kernel in ORT, we need to explicitly specify which stream to launch it.

title: OnnxRuntime multithreading efficiency is poor
body:
input is 1000 same queries ,the query for each request is the same,50-way multi-threaded concurrency:

onnxruntime cpu is 3000%, every request cost time, tensorflow is 60ms, and onnxruntime is 27ms,onnx is more than 2 times faster than tensorflow,

But the  very strange phenomenon is:

1000 different queries,every query is different,50-way multi-threaded concurrency:
onnxruntime cpu is 1500%,every request cost time, tensorflow is 60ms, and onnxruntime is 90ms,onnx is much slower than tensorflow

1-way concurrency onnxruntime cpu is 100%,and every request cost time is 15ms, tensorflow is 30ms.


My server configuration is 40 cpu cores,and the onnxruntime set up is:
		
	 session_options.SetInterOpNumThreads(1);
     session_options.SetIntraOpNumThreads(1);
	 export OMP_NUM_THREADS=1
	 

	 
I don't know how to explain this phenomenon, why the onnx cpu is very low

title: Dependency issues with Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb

labels.name: status:wontfix
labels.description: This will not be worked on

body:
Hi,

We are having issues with .NET core 2.2 web projects referencing Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime (1.2.0).
The web projects is hosted in Azure as an app service (Microsoft.Web/sites).

The nuget package has a dependency for Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb, and since we remove all .pdbs before we publish to cloud, the web app crashses with a 502.5 error code.

Solutions we've found:
- Leaving the _\bin\runtimes\win-x86\Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb_ (obviously)
- Removing the _\bin\runtimes\win-x86\Windows.AI.MachineLearning.pdb_ reference from the *deps.json file

We'd rather not keep a .pdb that is over 50 Mb per runtime project referencing the nuget, and we haven't found any other solution to the *deps.json reference than removing it post build with Powershell.

_We also see some very large files in \bin\runtimes\ for osx and linux, which we of course can remove post build, but it feels a bit odd that the runtimes directory is over 600 Mb for some dependencies._ Edit: realized this is most certainly on us for not publishing to a specific runtime/framework in TeamCity.

Also tested around with [ExcludeAssets settings](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/consume-packages/package-references-in-project-files) in the *.csproj / nuget reference without any luck.

This is a related issue / solution we found:
https://github.com/klalle/Microsoft.ML.onnxruntime_UWP_fix

So basically we _can_ solve the issue, but would like to know the reason for the .pdb dependency, and what your recommendations / solution to the above is? It's not an issue we've ever had with other Nuget packages.

Kind regards,
Emil

title: iOS cross build on MacOS
body:
**Description**: Enable iOS cross build on MacOS

**Motivation and Context**
The current iOS cross build (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3298) runs on Linux, the problems with it, 
1. Requires complicated tool chain setup
2. Does not currently build iOS simulator, you cannot create iOS CI from the arm/arm64 binary
3. Cannot easily switch target OS version (ios12, ios13, ...)

The motivation is to use XCode to build iOS on MacOS, since most iOS developers will have Mac as dev machine.
Enabled in this PR
- X86_64 iphonesimulator
- Arm64 iphoneOS

Also enabled building use XCode on MacOS
This will not remove the iOS cross build on linux, that part will be kept unchanged

Usage,
On MacOS, Install latest XCode, run
./build.sh --config Debug --ios --ios_sysroot iphonesimulator --osx_arch x86_64 --apple_deploy_target 13 --skip_test --use_xcode

Not yet addressed,
1. Build arm/arm64 binary. will add it later,
**[Resolved]** Have to add a ios.cmake file based on this issue of cmake (https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/issues/20013#note_731872)

2. --parallel option is not current supported by xcodebuild, need to figure out how to add it
**[Resolved]** 

3. arm64 compiling has link warning, ld: warning: arm64 function not 4-byte aligned: _MlasSgemmKernelZero ...
**[Resolved]** 

Issues
1. The apple clang will fail to build the mlas assembly using i386 flavor for iphonesimulator
2. This iOS cross compile does not support armv7/v7s (32bit) for now
For both issues above, since Apple is dropping the support for 32bit iOS, will not fix this here, unless there is demand on support legacy devices using iOS 10 and older.

title: Set gradient as output only for easy mode
body:
Currently gradients are added to graph outputs by default. This causes extra memory usage that cant be reused for the outputs. 
Gradients are specifically required as outputs for easy mode, so setting the config accordingly will save memory (same amount as the static model size).

Fix training modification of Graph SetInputs() and SetOutputs(). Originally there were distinct code paths in Graph based on whether the graph was loaded from a GraphProto or created from scratch. The training modifications made that distinction a bit ambiguous - i.e., even though the Graph is loaded from a GraphProto for training, sometimes we rely on the other code path, e.g., to deduce the graph inputs after modifying it. title: Support GPU Event Operators
body:
We implement GPU `WaitEvent` and `RecordEvent` to

- avoid copy between GPU and CPU, and
- support in-place update for tensors passing through `WaitEvent` and `RecordEvent`. We will have a pattern `bias_grad` -> `WaitEvent` -> `bias_grad_waited` -> `Lamb` -> `bias_update_direction`. We want `Lamb` to reuse the memory of `bias_grad` to store `bias_update_direction`.

title: Improve node and node argument name generation
body:
This PR adds the efforts in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3638 to master branch. This change has two benefits.

- it ensures the uniqueness of names at graph level.
- it avoids the change of names when possible. This is quite annoying if ORT keep renaming variables when, for example, adding a new graph transformer.

Q: Why we don't use a global naming manager?
A: 

- If we move the name generator out of graph, there will be two places we check if a name is usable: 1) inside graph's name-generating functions 2) inside name manager's name generator. This is error-prone and largely reduces readability.
- Having a global name manager implies that manager knows all the names. However, the implication is not correct. The global name manager is not aware of pre-stored names such as initializer names in ONNX model.
- The above two points may be resolved with a 10x large change. Basically, every places which uses names need to be replaced with some functions in the global name manager.

title: Add Distributed Checkpointing support
body:
This PR adds the following support:
save_checkpoint() and load_checkpoint() support to ORTTrainer.
Ability to save and load in the following scenarios:
1) Save zero checkpoints, load in zero-enabled model with same number of ranks
2) Load partitioned checkpoints(FP32 weights, FP16 weights, Optimizer params) into non-partitioned run
3) Save and load in non-zero case.

It also changes the way moment names are generated to make the naming deterministic for ease of save and load to the form:
Moment_<1 or 2>_<weight_name>_view _ <view_num>

title: Avoid appending index to names when possible
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Our name generator currently generate names like "Bias3" even if "Bias" is not used by anyone. This PR ensures "Bias" is still "Bias" when possible.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Each time upstream script changes, I need to open Neutron again to find the right name. This process is very annoying when implementing new features (such as pipeline).
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Add a pipeline for Linux ARM64 python package
body:
**Description**:

1. Support cross-compiling the python package for ARM. Validated with the latest linaro toolchain: gcc--7.5.0-2019.12 for ARM64.
2. Add a pipeline for it.

If we want to support more compiler versions, like the 4.8.3 used by raspberry pi, we need to suppress more warnings. It's easy to do. But so far we don't have such requirement, so I discarded these changes from this PR. 

I'll add a doc later.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Not use OpenMP for android build
body:
**Description**: Load the Android lib in an Android Project will throw error on "library "libomp.so" not found" 

There is an issue in Android NDK (https://github.com/android/ndk/issues/1028) for OpenMP you would have to static link the OpenMP lib,
This is to disable OpenMP for android build

title: Downgrade numpy requirement to 1.16.6
body:
**Description**: 

This PR is similar to #2758 except version number is changed to 1.16.6

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

Per suggestion from @jywu-msft and @guschmue :
1.18.0 was only released on Dec 22, 2019. Many users wouldn't like requiring such new software. and we don't even use numpy 1.18 specific api's in ORT.

See the discussion at #3003

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Add Lamb Shape Inference
